# On the Efficiency of Persistent Data Structures

## Abstract

We present a comprehensive analysis of persistent data structures and their amortized time complexity. Our results show that path copying combined with lazy evaluation achieves $O(\log n)$ amortized time for most operations. We introduce a novel technique for reducing the constant factor in persistent balanced trees.

## Introduction

Persistent data structures preserve previous versions of themselves when modified[^driscoll1989]. Unlike ephemeral data structures, which support only a single version, persistent structures maintain a version history.

This property is essential for:

- Functional programming languages
- Version control systems
- Database transaction logs
- Undo/redo mechanisms

## Background

### Persistence Levels

Full persistence
: Any version can be queried or updated

Partial persistence
: Any version can be queried, only the latest updated

Confluent persistence
: Versions can be combined (merged)

### Related Work

Driscoll et al.[^driscoll1989] introduced the fat node and path copying techniques. Okasaki[^okasaki1998] developed purely functional approaches using lazy evaluation.

## Our Approach

We define the cost of an operation on version $v$ as:

$$
C(v) = T_{access}(v) + T_{copy}(v) + T_{rebalance}(v)
$$

Where $T_{access}$ is the time to locate the node, $T_{copy}$ is the path copying cost, and $T_{rebalance}$ is the structural adjustment cost.

### Amortized Analysis

Using the potential method, we assign a potential $\Phi$ to each version:

$$
\hat{c}_i = c_i + \Phi_i - \Phi_{i-1}
$$

The amortized cost $\hat{c}_i$ accounts for both the actual cost $c_i$ and the change in potential.

## Results

| Structure | Ephemeral | Persistent (ours) | Previous Best |
| --- | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| Balanced BST | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log^2 n)$ |
| Hash Table | $O(1)$ | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n)$ |
| Priority Queue | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n \cdot \log \log n)$ |

Table: Comparison of amortized time complexities {#results-table}

## Conclusion

We have demonstrated that persistent balanced BSTs can achieve the same amortized time complexity as their ephemeral counterparts. Future work includes extending these results to concurrent persistent structures.

[^driscoll1989]: Driscoll, J.R. et al. (1989). Making Data Structures Persistent.
[^okasaki1998]: Okasaki, C. (1998). Purely Functional Data Structures.
